spanGrp.span: Should I say mine (name) in English?
Hąąp Hanį_Guįga Hąąp Hanį_Guįga hįįgaire waaʔųnąkšąną.
"Going after Daylight", "Going after daylight" they call me, I am here sitting.
Hąįnįxjįk eegi haastįk hagihi haʔe_haakjene cii eejaxjį.
In the morning, then, I picked blueberries near the house.
The Indians used to pick blueberries .
Ceekjį ceekjį heesgera hanąąxgųra, hąąhą wąąk hiʔącįk haara
The first thing I heard, yes, my male (?) father
ceexji cexjihesgera haną́xgųną, ha'a, wąąkhianįk haara
they call him (father) "All kinds of clouds" (Thunderclan).
Hiʔąc haara hiyą hiʔąc hinųųpra Heenąra
One of my fathers brothers, the second one
hi'anc haara hiyaa (hižą) hiąk hinųbra heenąną
žeʔe ceekji wažą haastįk gihi gihiire <<ui>> eeja horakire horakšąną.
he (father) told that they told that they used to picked blueberries.
že'e ceexji wažą haastįk gihi gihire 'eja hoorákire horakšą́ą
something missing between "gihire" and "'eja" -- LP: Yes, added <<ui>>.
Wąąkšik sʼiireją hegų wąąkšikra stoohiire nįgešąną hiirešųnųšgųnį.
The Indians used to live scattered in groups.
wąąkšik hireša hegų́ wąąkšíkra stoohire nįgešanąk (?) hiirešųunNšgųnį
Haastįk gihiire wąąkšikra nįgešąną hoxatap eeja nįge gihiire.
They used to pick blueberries here and there in the bush.
haastįk gihíre wąąkšíkra niigéšąną hoxatáp 'eja niige gihiire
Žeesge (he)gų cii hociire hąąhąʔo waipere cii hoci(ire) hesgešge hiirešųnųną.
žeesge niige (gųų) cihociire aaho waipére cii ho(ci)
hesgešge = anaphora; used to refer to whatever was said before
"nįge" really said? -- LP: No, deleted from tx and mo.
Nąąnį eera eeja cii_hoijas hociire hegų žeegų stoo ųire.
My mother (says) they used to live in groups together in the tent.
nąnįhera eja nąnįhera eja ciihoicas hociire heguže stol'ųine
Eegi eegi hąąpregi hota hegų nįheižą hegų nįge howaraire haastįk gihiire.
Some of them go in a group and go away picking berries.
'egi 'egi hąpregi hotá huniheža hegų niigé howaraire haastink gihire
Hota cii eejašge wąąkrašge hegų eeja žeesge hiirešųnų aireną.
Some of the men stayed home, that's what they used to do; it was said.
hotá ciiejasge wąankrašge eja hegų žesge hirešųnų aireen
"eja" and "hegų" other way round? -- LP: I think so, swapped on tx and mo.
That's the way they used to do it ... and there ...
'eegi 'eeja seem to belong to the following sentence and function as HESIT
Wąąk hiʔącįk haara žeeja howajišge tʼeenąšge hegų wažą wainąsara ųųšgųnį.
That's where it came from, said the father, my father, he had TB
'egi wąąk hi'anjįkhaara žeeja howaajisge 'eenašge hegų wažą waínašára (mąmąnašara)) 'ųšgunį
really "'egi" at the beginning? -- LP: Don't think so, removed on tx and mo.
Eeja jaaji eeja jaaji eera hakaranį ųųnaak nįį_haicep hakaranį ųųnąąk eeja nįį_haicep hųųgirakirešųnų.
They took care of him, my father, and he died (lost his breath), I heard that, that's what they used to tell me.
egi jaji esge eja jaji heera hakarani'ųnaák eja niihaicep hakarani'ųnaák eja niihaicep hųgirak reešųnų
beginning: "'eeja jaaji eeja jaaji 'ee-ra..."?; removed one "eja"; transcription doesn't seem to match spoken words from "niihaicep" -- LP: Changed beginning accordingly, not sure about the end.
Eegi žee žeegų haʔų huuwi hagoreižą hegų žeegų ųųsge (he)gų eegi Nįįš herege (he)gų eegi aašge haciwi.
And then we are coming to Wisconsin Dells and we lived close by.
'egi že žegų ha'ųhųwi hagoreiža hegų žeegu 'ųsgé gų 'egi niišerege gų 'egi 'aašge haciwi
Nąąnį eera hegų nąąnį eera jaaji eera eesge hegų gooja
My mother and my dad over there
nani heera hegų naani heera jaji heere eesge hegų gojá
hąąhąʔą jaagušge Necedah airegająšgųnį eeja heesge hagihi hahiwi.
we went picking to Necedah, I suppose.
aha'a jagųšge Necedah airegaja šgunį 'eja hesge hagihahiwi
Gųha hąąp nųųp hąąp taanį (he)gų eesge hagiwi.
We arrived there in two or three days.
gųha hąąP hąąp nųp taní gų eesge hagiwí
switched "hąąp" and "nųųp" -- LP: Yes, also switched on tx.
Heesge hakiriwi hegų hoxjąnągi nąąnį eera hagijite haasnąąka eegi hoxjąnąga nįge peex hožu.
I helped mother to put berries in cans in the evening.
hege hagiwi hegų huxjanąkgi naneera hakijite haasnákga egi huxcanąkga nįįgé peex hozu
Hegų hąąp nųųp taanį haʔųwi hogihi hižą hakįnį peex hožu žeegų hii.
We did that for two or three days, she filled over hundred bottles.
hegų hąąp nųųpa tąąį ha 'ųwin hogihiša (ha)kįįn peex hozu jeegu hii
Eegi mąąnį nee hiire. Hegų hegų tee hegų waruhoire žuura ųų nąąʔįire
During the winter they did this. They donate trying to make money.
egi mąąni nehire hegų hegų tee hegų waruxhoire žuura 'ųnąne
Hegų jaaji eera waruho hii nąąnį eera nąąc_hisgi.
My father went to donate (the berries), and mother scolded at him (probably because he gave away too much).
hegų jaji hera waruxohi nanį hera nąąciski
Ka eeja ka eeja (hąą)ke peex waažunį waruhokje wagiʔųire.
I didn't can those jars for being donated.
ka 'eja ka 'eje ke peex waažunį waruhokje wagi'uine
Žee nee hįyarucikjawi yaarege waaʔų eegi eeja Jaaji eera eeja nąąc_hisgiiregają.
My father was scolded, we could eat that, I thought.
že nee hiaruucikkjnawi yaarége waa'ų egi 'eja jaji heera eja nąącisgire gaja
Hegų haawišunų hegų gipįesge hegų taakac hegų.
Thats the way we used to do it even when it was hot and it was a pleasant time.
hegų haawišunų hegų gipįesge hegų taakac hegų
Hegų raawąkšge kiza nįge haʔųwi žee hegų nįįsge žeegu hąąpteʔe.
We fought the mosquitos all over, that's the way it used to be and that's the way it is today.
hegų rawąksge kiisa niigé ha'ųwi že hegų niisge žegu hąąpte'e
That's not the right thing, but I like it now.
kesgenigają hegų žesge že haipįįnį hegųnige
(Hąą)kešge (hąą)kešge (he)gų hacįįjašge howatanąki hegų haassįcga hagikje heesganį.
I don't know where to go to pick berries anymore.
keesge kašgegų (kešge) hajįja-šge howataanągi hegų "Haašįcga" hagikšesganį
Žee ųųsge woorak hanįra hįįgirera hijąhį hišekjanawi.
This is the end of the story, someone else should talk now.
